author: @codestorywithMIK
text:
I rarely comment on videos, but this time i had to.
Thank you so much for sharing this beautiful and inspiring story. It hit me hard. I still remember those days when my parents struggled to pay my school fees because of my father's financial condition. When I moved to a new city for college, we had to borrow money from relatives to make ends meet. Those moments of helplessness became the fuel that made me push harder every single day.
Today, I feel grateful that I can give my parents the comfort they never asked for but always deserved. I don’t like posting materialistic things on social media , somehow it never made sense to me. Peace, gratitude, and seeing my parents smile matter more than any car or fancy gadget ever could.

Thank you again for reminding us that silent sacrifices and quiet determination can shape extraordinary journeys. Not all success needs to be loud, some stories live in the hearts of those who went through the storm and came out stronger.

With Gratitude -🙏❤️🙏
codestorywithMIK

author: @rajjogi77
text:
I grew up in a small town called Jamshedpur, Jharkhand. We lived in a rented house where even the ₹500 monthly rent was often beyond our means — overdue for years at a time. I remember countless Diwalis without sweets or crackers, and many days without food or a gas cylinder to cook with.

My father spent nearly a decade away from home, doing whatever odd jobs he could find. My mother worked tirelessly — in NGOs, and at one point, even as a maid — just to keep us going.

Yet through it all, there was one thing my mother never compromised on: education.
We had nothing — hand-me-down books and notebooks — but my brother and I studied in the ICSE board. We never went to school functions or picnics; even a ₹300 fee was out of reach. I remember missing one event because I didn’t have clothes decent enough to wear.

Today, life has changed. I'm married now and recently moved to the U.S. I won’t say I’ve “made it” — I have no assets, no land, no big bank balance. But I know I’m on the path. I believe that within the next decade, I’ll be part of the top 20%.

The bottom line is this: Poverty is brutal. Most don’t make it to the other side. But the only real weapons against it are education and an unrelenting hunger to change your life. Nothing else matters.

To anyone who’s still in that phase — keep going. Education is your only weapon. Education, and hunger.

author: @abhishekrai1840
text:
Feeling stuck in life? You’re not alone! Many face challenges that seem insurmountable. Let's explore how we can overcome negativity and embrace personal growth together.

In our latest video 'Are You Stuck?', we delve into the pressing issue of negativity and how it impacts personal growth.

The journey of individuals like Dalpreet and Anita Devi illustrates that despite challenging backgrounds, transformation is achievable. Dalpreet's story, from financial struggles and academic setbacks to finding success as a college tutor and later in professional life, exemplifies resilience. He faced societal odds with only a 3% chance of rising above his circumstances but chose education and hard work over despair.

Similarly, Anita Devi's experience highlights the transformative power of community support. From battling depression to becoming a successful entrepreneur through mushroom farming, her journey emphasizes that opportunities often arise from adversity.

These narratives are not just tales of struggle; they serve as powerful reminders that embracing change can lead us to better circumstances. Education and the courage to take risks, as shown by both Dalpreet and Anita, can pave the way for success while empowering others along the way. Together, we can redefine what’s possible, proving that our current situations don’t dictate our futures.

Share your thoughts on overcoming challenges in the comments or explore more about our journey toward personal growth!
